  "title": "5.2\tFINDINGS",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "83cd35fcb486b1f5",
      "text": "**(1)** Relationship between Farmers and Pastoralists. This is an age-long economic and nutritional relationship which   can neither be easily broken nor wished away. However, many factors have adversely affected the relationship. Such factors include environmental, political, economic and social changes and these have seriously undermined the relationship. "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "63ce66d744100a21",
      "text": "As earlier observed, the old relationship was symbiotic and complementary instead of the conflictual relationship that existing between the two groups. The transition from pre-colonial to colonial and to post-colonial times have contributed to straining the relationship and this has been further worsened by environmental degradation. The gradual desertification arising from the effect of climate change has forced the pastoralists to move southwards in search of pastures in areas that were traditionally occupied by farmers, thus generating conflicts between the two groups.  "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "398d2912c93a193a",
      "text": "**(2)** The present relationship is characterized by hatred, rancour, bitterness, distrust etc. which occasionally degenerates to violence. Farmers are particularly worried that Bororo Fulani pastoralists enter their farms and destroy their crops with impunity. This feeling of helplessness drove the farmers to self-help that results to violence, killing, and loss of properties on both sides."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "7feec4509863f730",
      "text": "**(3)** Lack of effective machinery for managing the conflict. Hitherto, there was no effective early warning system to prevent conflicts from degenerating to violence. Somehow, one gets the impression that those saddled with the responsibility of managing the conflicts seem not to have a clue to transforming them.  At best, the problem has been tackled in a reactive rather than proactive way. The law made by the State Government, for instance, does not take into consideration the problem of pastoralists looking for food and water for their herds especially during the dry season. "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "70c52d732c6b1723",
      "text": "Rather, the law prescribes punishment for any pastoralist who enters farms and destroyed crops. The State Government could turn round to say that it has responsibility mainly for its citizens and not for pastoralists who are mostly nomads roaming about looking for pasture and water. However, until a holistic solution is found to the problem of pastoralists, there may be no end to the conflicts between them and farmers and the resultant occasional eruption of violence."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "4fe2d97eefac03b0",
      "text": "**(4)** At the time of this investigation, an uneasy calm exists in Saki West Local Government area. This is because the incidence of invasion of farms by Bororo Fulanis still occurs on a regular basis and there is palpable tension in the area. This was why the meetings (referred to above) between the Saki Parapo and Sarkin Fulanis and other stakeholders in the area were held late last year. How far this would go in preventing further eruption of violence remains to be seen. It should be stated, however, that the farmers and hunters remain alert and battle ready because the fragile peace can snap any time."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "6ce2c2f3abef1cca",
      "text": "**(5)** Perception Problem. The issue of perception which is common in inter-ethnic relationship is worsened in this case by deep acrimony between the farmers and pastoralists in the Local Government area. Ordinarily, the ethnic difference between Yorubas and Fulanis makes one to deal with the other in a condescending manner but the way Bororo Fulanis invade and destroy farms callously tends to reinforce the belief of Yoruba farmers that the Bororos are homeless and stateless people who are virtually uncontrollable. Bororos on the other hand regard the farmers as wicked people who seize and kill their cows at the slightest excuse. The point that is being made is that perception problem fuels the conflict. "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "81299f7372f050ff",
      "text": "**(6)** Underage Bororo Fulani Pastoralists Herding Cattle. There are instances of underage Bororo Fulanis herding cattle. Farmers complained that these young herders are sometimes unable to control the flock of cows in their charge and such cows easily stray into farms and destroy their crops."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "c87974ced5cf9054",
      "text": "**(7)** Federal Governmentâ€™s Proposed Intervention. Following persistent outbreak of violent conflicts between farmers and pastoralists in various parts of the country especially in the north, the Federal Government has decided to take action to resolve the problem. In a nationwide broadcast on Tuesday, 25th March, 2014, the Minister of Agriculture, Dr. Akinwumi Adesina stated that the following solutions would be provided:"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "0e297518b2652080",
      "text": "(a) Creation of Grazing Reserves.  Grazing zones would be mapped out and developed in various parts of the country and provided for the use of pastoralists."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "f9e00aa8a1d1df8c",
      "text": "(b) Re- introduction of Grazing Corridors.\n\tEstablishment of Cattle Track. Cattle tracks will be introduced across the country to facilitate the movement of pastoralists without invading farms.  \n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "05cacd4aa31ff649",
      "text": "(c) Satellite Image Sensing.\nIn addition, image sensing would be used through satellite to track the movement of nomads and their herds so as to prevent infiltration into the farms and prevent destruction of crops in the farmlands.The same tracking system would be monitored for early warning signs so that conflicts could be nipped in bud before they become escalated.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "be52c2fa296ab603",
      "text": "(d) Adequate Communication and Networking.\nAdequate communication tools such as smart phones which had been provided for farmers would also be deployed in calling up appropriate authorities whenever their crops are threatened by grazers.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "78512b6eca70a344",
      "text": "(e) Monitoring by Agriculture Extension Workers.\nAgriculture Extension Workers are to be trained to provide intelligence and meaningful intervention at the community level and report to security agencies for further action.\n"
